				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">How Much Should We Pay For Art?</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Anna North			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-06-08T14:46:17+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">June 8, 2014 10:46 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">June 8, 2014 10:46 am</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content"><div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/06/07/opinion/nyto-katy/nyto-katy-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/06/07/opinion/nyto-katy/nyto-katy-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/06/07/opinion/nyto-katy/nyto-katy-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000002926728" width="592" height="586" alt=""   /><meta itemprop="height" content="586"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text"></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Chad Batka for The New York Times</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//op-talk.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/06/08/how-much-should-we-pay-for-art/" data-title="How Much Should We Pay For Art?" data-description="When so much is free online, ANNA NORTH writes, how do we determine the value of creative work?">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âHow do we decide, as a capitalist society, what creative expression is worth?â That question, <a href="//thebillfold.com/2014/06/assigning-value-to-art-music-and-reality-tv/">posed</a> by Ester Bloom at The Billfold, gets more vexed every day.Â In a time when more and more art is available for free online, we as a society have to figure out how to value and support it.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Ms. Bloom notes that the answers our economy comes up with donât always make much sense. Citing a recent <a href="//www.slate.com/blogs/moneybox/2014/05/22/what_bands_charge_to_play_macklemore_earns_more_than_kendrick.html">list</a> at Slate of what musical acts make per live show, she writes:</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âYou could get Alanis Morrisette to play five times for the same price youâd pay to have Katy Perry play once. Your soul would thank you. So would my disaffected high-school self. Doesnât it all seem kind of arbitrary?â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">She also points to a Los Angeles Times <a href="//www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/cotown/la-fi-ct-unscripted-consolidation-20140603-story.html#page=1">story</a> identifying a âgold rushâ in reality TV, with big conglomerates paying hundreds of millions for stakes in the smaller production companies that make shows like âDuck Dynastyâ and âMarriage Boot Camp: Bridezillas.â That gold rush could be more of a bubble â one insider told The Los Angeles Times the market for &#8220;Bridezilla&#8221; content was âoverheated.â And itâs easy to imagine executives regretting their multimillion-dollar purchases if viewers tire of angry brides. For now, though, says Ms. Bloom, âas a society we have an insatiable desire for the entertainment provided by people behaving badly, especially people who are the extremes of rich or poor, thin or fat, feminine or masculine.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Such entertainment is worth suitcases full of cash, at least to big television companies, while itâs become popular to argue that a documentary film, for instance, should be available for free. In her recent book â<a href="//www.hiddendriver.com/projects/the-peoples-platform">The Peopleâs Platform</a>,â Astra Taylor describes her unsuccessful attempts to get people to take down copies of her documentary film that theyâd posted online â one person, she writes, âremarked that since my film was about philosophy and since philosophy, in a moral and historical sense, belongs to everyone in the world, my film does, too.â Sheâs not wholly unsympathetic to this point of view, but she identifies a drawback in it:</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âMy aim has been to make philosophy more accessible by using the power of cinema to convey ideas that might intimidate or bore in another context. The problem is that making movies is not cheap, even in this age of digital video, and support for unusual projects is dwindling.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">If nobody has to pay to see her documentaries, she may not be able to make them â and then, of course, the ideas therein wonât reach anybody at all. In a <a href="//branch.com/b/art-disruption">Branch conversation</a> recently launched by Latoya Peterson of Al Jazeera America, a number of artists and critics raised similar concerns. Molly Crabapple, an artist and journalist, wrote:</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWeâre beings with finite time who tire and have kids and get sick and die, and need money to sustain life.Â It costs nothing to reproduce a song.Â But the artist who made that song still has to live.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In an email to Op-Talk, she added broad policy prescriptions: âOn a larger level, the best ways to support artists are the best ways to support humans: free health care, a generous social safety net, social security payments high enough to provide a dignified old age.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Alyssa Rosenberg, a culture blogger at The Washington Post, noted in the Branch that the Internet has been, for artists, something of a double-edged sword:</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWeb-based tools like Twitter can help build audiences for specific pieces of art â Shonda Rhimesâ â and give people power within big corporations or institutions.Â But it can also drive down prices in ways that have a huge impact on artistsâ abilities to make a living.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">She also pointed out in an e-mail to Op-Talk that some of the same technologies that have driven prices down can also be used to support creative projects:</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âFile-sharing undermined the record industry, of course. But in response to that, companies like Amazon and iTunes have developed platforms that make it much easier for artists and labels to sell individual songs and that offer real advantages to consumers who want to access their files from a lot of devices.Â Streaming services have made it easier for consumers to graze widely when it comes to television and movies, and gotten them used to paying low fees, or not paying at all for that content. But if you want to make and distribute a web series, there are options for doing that, ways for viewers to find your content, and means for you to get advertising placed on your episodes so you can get something back.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Will the Internet help artists more than it harms them? For Ms. Rosenberg, âitâs really early to tell.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Whatever the case, itâs not just artists who feel its effects â Ms. Taylor argues that the prevalence of free stuff can change how we all think about art. She writes:</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âArt and culture are nonetheless vital, essential even, to what it means to be human, yet digital abundance has diminished our sense of their worth.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âDoes it follow that culture has value only if there is a limited supply to drive up demand? And what is it that makes some bits worth paying for â food for a virtual pet, a video game app, or a song on iTunes â and others â an article, a streaming video, a photograph â not?â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The second question is similar to Ms. Bloomâs, and itâs one that we, as a culture, havenât fully answered yet. Or, that is, market forces have answered it for us: Art that gets paid for today is typically art that helps a company get a return on its investment. But as many are beginning to point out, thatâs not the only possible answer, or necessarily the best one.</p>
	</div>
